Let's denote the number of members in the band by \(N\). When the members are arranged in 8 rows, there are 2 positions unoccupied, which means the number of members is \(8k - 2\) for some integer \(k\). Similarly, when the members are arranged in 9 rows, there are 3 positions unoccupied, which means the number of members is \(9m - 3\) for some integer \(m\). Therefore, we have the system of congruences: \[
\begin{cases}
N \equiv -2 \pmod{8} \\
N \equiv -3 \pmod{9}
\end{cases}
\] which can be rewritten as \[
\begin{cases}
N \equiv 6 \pmod{8} \\
N \equiv 6 \pmod{9}
\end{cases}
\] The smallest positive integer that satisfies both congruences is the least common multiple of 8 and 9 plus 6. The least common multiple of 8 and 9 is 72, so the smallest positive integer that satisfies both congruences is \(72 + 6 = 78\). The general solution is \(N = 72t + 78\) for some integer \(t\). We need to find the values of \(t\) such that \(100 \leq 72t + 78 \leq 200\). This simplifies to \[
100 \leq 72t + 78 \leq 200
\] Subtracting 78 from all parts of the inequality, we get \[
22 \leq 72t \leq 122
\] Dividing by 72, we get \[
\frac{22}{72} \leq t \leq \frac{122}{72}
\] Simplifying the fractions, we get \[
0.3055 \leq t \leq 1.6944
\] Since \(t\) must be an integer, the only possible value for \(t\) is 1. Therefore, \(N = 72 \cdot 1 + 78 = 150\). So the number of members in the band is \(\boxed{150}\) <answer>150</answer>

